A cognitive exercise app designed to support memory, attention, and logic in older adults through accessible, research-informed interactions.

Overview

Designing cognitive training for an aging population

As part of IAT 351: Advanced Human-Computer Interaction, my group developed Memora, a cross-platform application optimized for iPad that makes cognitive exercise accessible to older adults aged 55-75 through a comprehensive, research-backed design. The app engages users in short, evidence-based cognitive exercises to enhance memory and attention, serving as both a preventive measure and a potential delay of cognitive decline, including early effects of dementia.

The Problem

  • Cognitive decline affects memory, attention, and daily functioning in adults 55-75
  • Most cognitive training apps are designed for younger users
  • Small UI elements, complex gestures, and heavy gamification create accessibility barriers
  • Many apps prioritize engagement mechanics over usability and clarity

The Opportunity

  • Design specifically for age-related changes in vision, motor control, and cognition
  • Ground exercises in evidence-backed cognitive research
  • Create an intuitive, respectful experience that promotes independence
  • Align with UN SDG 3: Good Health & Well-Being

Research & Discovery

Understanding elderly interaction patterns

I led research into how age-related sensory, cognitive, and motor changes affect mobile app interaction. Rather than applying generic accessibility guidelines, we designed specifically for aging users.

Designing for Human Performance

Sensory & Visual Changes

Older adults often experience reduced contrast sensitivity and slower reading speeds.

Design decisions

  • Larger default font sizes with adjustable text controls
  • Clean sans-serif typography
  • Warm, medium-contrast colour palette
  • Generous spacing between UI elements

Cognitive Processing

Older adults benefit from recognition over recall and clear feedback.

Design decisions

  • Linear navigation structure
  • Icons paired with text labels
  • Clear state changes and confirmation feedback
  • Reduced multitasking and screen clutter

Motor & Touch Interactions

Fine motor precision may decrease with age.

Design decisions

  • Large touch targets
  • Single-tap interactions
  • No multi-finger gestures
  • Designed primarily for tablet or iPad use, allowing for increased target size

Evidence-Based Exercise Selection

Rather than using generic "brain games," we selected exercises supported by research on cognitive aging.

Memory Exercises

Match-style games using familiar household objects to support episodic and recognition memory.

Attention Games

Visual search tasks designed to strengthen selective attention and processing speed.

Logic Challenges

Pattern and reasoning exercises targeting problem-solving and executive function.

Daily Practice Tracking

Short 5-10 minute sessions to encourage habit formation and reduce cognitive fatigue.

Designing for User Experience

Emotional & Motivational Feedback

Positive reinforcement improves engagement and memory performance.

Design decisions

  • Friendly time-based greetings ("Good Evening")
  • Encouraging completion messages
  • No punitive streak counters

Familiar Mental Models

Everyday objects are easier to recognize and recall than abstract forms.

Design decisions

  • Household items in memory games
  • Card-based layouts
  • Minimal abstract symbolism

Progress & Self-Tracking

Seeing progress increases motivation and continued engagement.

Design decisions

  • Monthly statistics view
  • Tracking the time spent on each activity
  • Simple data visualization

Design Process

From research insights to interface design

Using our research findings, I established design principles and co-created prototypes in Figma, iterating based on accessibility guidelines and team feedback. Visual assets and illustrations were created in Procreate using a semi-realist art style to avoid overstimulation.

1. Large Touch Targets

All interactive elements meet accessibility standards with generous spacing to prevent errors and accommodate reduced motor precision.

2. High Contrast & Readability

Sans-serif fonts (Helvetica) with three adjustable sizes to accommodate varying visual acuity. Warm, medium-saturation colour palette for emotional engagement and clarity.

3. Simple, Direct Navigation

Linear navigation structure with clearly labeled buttons. Users can always return to the home screen without complex paths.

4. Familiar Mental Models

Card-based layouts featuring everyday household objects that users recognize, supporting memory recall and aligning with pre-existing mental models (Hoefeijzers et al., 2017).

Key Design Decisions

1. Colour-Coded Game Categories

Each game type has a distinct colour, allowing users to quickly identify exercise types at a glance without needing to read labels.

2. Positive Reinforcement Over Streak Pressure

Friendly greetings and progress messages frame engagement positively. No streak counters that could feel punitive if a day is missed.

3. Monthly Progress Summaries

Progress is organized by month rather than day, reducing pressure and encouraging broader reflection on improvement over time.

4. Simplified Data Visualization

Statistics are presented as three clear metrics — exercises completed, accuracy, and total time — rather than complex charts or dashboards.

Development

Translating design to React Native

I co-implemented the final designs in React Native, ensuring our accessibility decisions carried through to the functional app. Firebase was integrated as the cloud-based backend to support data persistence, user authentication, and progress tracking functionalities.

Technical Implementation

Component architecture: Built a global settings system using React Context that persists user preferences to Firebase and propagates changes across the entire app instantly.

Weekly progress tracking: Built a weekly challenge system that calculates the current week, resets progress automatically on rollover, and prevents duplicate completions.

Accessibility state management: User accessibility preferences reset to safe defaults on sign out and reload per-user from Firebase on sign in, so settings are always scoped to the person using the device. 

// Accessible font scaling — SettingsContext.js
const scaleFontSize = (baseSize) => {
  const multiplier = getBaseFontSize() / 12;
  return baseSize * multiplier;
};

// Applied consistently across every screen component
<Text style={{ fontSize: scaleFontSize(16) }}>Settings</Text>

Challenges & Solutions

Challenge: Ensuring consistent, accessible touch target sizes across different device sizes, from phones in landscape to iPads, without hardcoding pixel values that would break on other screens.

Solution: Built a custom useResponsive hook that detects device type at runtime and exposes a unified set of layout values, such as padding or font sizes, which are used consistently across every screen. This meant that once a user's accessibility decisions were made, they automatically propagated throughout the system. 

// src/hooks/useResponsive.js
export const useResponsive = () => {
  const [dimensions, setDimensions] = useState(Dimensions.get('window'));

  useEffect(() => {
    const subscription = Dimensions.addEventListener('change', ({ window }) => {
      setDimensions(window);
    });
    return () => subscription?.remove();
  }, []);

  const isTablet = dimensions.width >= 768;

  return {
    isTablet,
    horizontalPadding: isTablet ? 40 : 24,
    verticalPadding:   isTablet ? 40 : 20,
    fontSize: {
      greeting:    isTablet ? 26 : 22,
      gameTitle:   isTablet ? 18 : 15,
    },
  };
};

Challenge: Providing meaningful visual feedback during the memory card game without using animations so complex or fast they'd disorient older adult users.

Solution: Implemented a 3D card flip using React Native's Animated API with a deliberate 300ms duration, which is fast enough to feel responsive but slow enough to track visually. backfaceVisibility: 'hidden' ensures only one face renders at a time, keeping the interaction simple. 

// Card flip animation — MemoryGameScreen.js
const flipAnim = useRef(new Animated.Value(0)).current;

useEffect(() => {
  Animated.timing(flipAnim, {
    toValue:         isFlipped || isMatched ? 1 : 0,
    duration:        300,  // intentionally measured — not jarring
    useNativeDriver: true,
  }).start();
}, [isFlipped, isMatched]);

const frontRotate = flipAnim.interpolate({
  inputRange:  [0, 1],
  outputRange: ['0deg', '180deg'],
});
const backRotate = flipAnim.interpolate({
  inputRange:  [0, 1],
  outputRange: ['180deg', '360deg'],
});

// Each face uses backfaceVisibility: 'hidden'
// so only one side is ever visible at a time

Final Solution

A complete cognitive training experience

The final application provides four evidence-based exercise categories with a simple, respectful interface designed specifically for older adults aged 55-75.

Home Screen

The home screen greets users by name with a personalized welcome and the current date, as well as the total challenges completed in the current month. Four labelled category cards link to the Daily Challenge, Memory Games, Attention Games, and Logic Games using large touch targets and distinct pastel colour coding for quick recognition. A daily streak counter in the top corner provides gentle motivation without pressure.

Dashboard

Logic Game - Making Connections

Making Connections presents users with four illustrated items and asks them to identify the odd one out, then select the shared connection category from three options. The dual-selection mechanic of picking the item and naming the rule, reinforces deductive reasoning and semantic memory. Illustrated card imagery uses familiar household objects to reduce cognitive load, while the shuffle and deselect controls support error recovery.

Question Screen

Progress Feedback

Memory Game - Matching Cards

Matching Cards challenges users to find eight pairs of illustrated household objects across a 4x4 grid. Cards flip with a smooth 300ms animation to avoid disorientation, and matched pairs remain face-up so users can track their progress. The completion screen reports accuracy, move count, and time elapsed metrics to reinforce a sense of accomplishment.

In-Game Screen

Results Screen

Attention Game - Odd One Out

Odd One Out trains pre-attentive vision and selective attention by presenting users with a field of moving shapes and asking them to tap the one that looks different. Rounds increase in difficulty, challenging users to maintain their focus under visual noise. The exercise is grounded in research showing that attentional training can slow age-related decline in filtering irrelevant information.

In-Game Screen

Results Screen

Progress Tracking - Statistics

The Statistics screen shows three key metrics of exercises completed, average accuracy, and total time. An activity history table below logs each session by date, game type, score, and duration, with filter tabs for Logic, Memory, and Attention categories. Monthly navigation allows users to review past performance.

Progress Dashboard

Accessibility Settings

The Settings screen gives users direct control over three key accessibility parameters. Text size can be switched between Normal, Large, and Extra Large to accommodate varying levels of visual acuity without requiring system-level changes. Some future implementation include a Colourblind Mode toggle and a Sound toggle allow users to personalise their experience further.

Reflection

Learnings & next steps

What I Learned

  • Research-driven design creates more effective solutions than assumptions. Grounding decisions in HCI theory and cognitive aging research produced a more accessible product.
  • Accessibility constraints can actually improve design for all users. Larger touch targets and clearer navigation benefit everyone, not just older adults.
  • Designing for aging users requires empathy and restraint. Avoiding infantilizing aesthetics while maintaining usability is a careful balance.

Challenges Overcome

  • Balancing visual interest with simplicity for our demographic without appearing too childish or demeaning.
  • Choosing exercises with solid research backing rather than relying on popular but unvalidated brain-training trends.
  • Maintaining design consistency across multiple developers.
  • Testing accessibility without direct access to elderly users by relying on guidelines and secondary research.

Future Improvements

If I could continue this project, I would:

Conduct usability testing with actual elderly users to validate our design decisions and identify pain points we might have missed.

Add difficulty scaling that adapts to individual performance without being obvious or discouraging.

Implement voice interactions as an alternative input method for users with limited mobility.

Build more accessibility features including colourblind settings to support the approximately 300 million people worldwide affected by colour vision deficiency, and multi-language support with culturally adapted content.

Build caregiver version allowing caregivers to manage multiple patient profiles and track progress, supporting healthcare practitioners in identifying cognitive issues for early intervention.

Impact & Alignment with SDG 3

Memora advances UN Sustainable Development Goal 3: Good Health and Well-Being by promoting preventive mental care, supporting long-term cognitive health, and enhancing quality of life for an aging population. Specifically, it contributes to SDG 3.4 by reducing premature mortality from non-communicable diseases through prevention and by promoting mental health and well-being.
